<opener><dateline><date>22 Dec 15</date></dateline></opener> 

<add> to the family<lb/>
whose letters I hope<lb/>
to be reading on Saturday, &amp; my best <lb/>
of best love to that curious little animal<lb/>
who has occupied so<lb/>
much if not the whole<lb/>
of her BW.<lb/>
<signed> WB Spender</signed></add>

<add>PS The Gen knows I  was<lb/>
up with the 107 Bde but <lb/>
has not said one word  on<lb/>
the subject</add>

<salute>My Pr</salute>
<p>You really seem to be getting quite excited over things,<lb/>
but you mustn't count too much on things. </p>
<p>Richardson will I hope travel on with this letter so<lb/>
he may turn up any day. Mayne has left. </p>
<p>Again I hear that the 16 Div is coming here after all<lb/>
 or bits of it. I do hope it's not true.</p>
<p>You may not have got my family letter with news of<lb/>
my visit to the 107 Bge, but you can let Sir EC know<lb/>
 that whereas <del>the</del> our officers have got on excellently with the Dublin<lb/>
&amp; other Irish Regt, the men have not done so equally, &amp;  in<lb/>
fact Douglas who of course was able to get much more into<lb/>
touch with the men told us that there would have been <lb/>
real trouble, if they had not been separating so soon. People<lb/>
who do not know the Ulster temperament - including many<lb/>
Ulstermen &#x2014; do not realize how they play with smouldering<lb/>
flames when they say that things are all right.</p>
<p>Is this my Xmas letter? I think so &amp; my little<lb/>
 Pr will find a corner very warm for her when she<lb/>
takes the wings of thought to it, &amp; tho' I should say it was anything
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="6569" facs="#L1916_2419_img_6569"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>but a comfortable corner</p>
<p>I have no doubt she can fit herself<lb/>
in it as snugly as she has done this past 2 <hi rend="superscript">1/2</hi> years &amp; more so.</p>
<p> I shall remember <del>yo</del> her perhaps just a little more than usual,<lb/>
tho' that won't be easy because.....(naturally because I have so many<lb/>
other things to think about ?).  </p>
<p> If no little parcel is on her table to display to the others<lb/>
as she likes to do so much, she can smile quietly to herself knowing<lb/>
that she is getting a really big present this time as soon as the<lb/>
 bw can come home &amp; settle it. Funny little animal I believe<lb/>
she would almost <del>as</del> sooner have a parcel with pink string than<lb/>
 <add>the</add> 5 bits of red paper called Govt bonds which I hope to be able to <lb/>
put into her paws &amp; which will I hope bring in at least 20<lb/>
little golden circles to her afterwards.</p>
<p>I had a very pleasant but quiet little dinner with the <lb/>
7 <hi rend="superscript">th</hi> Div last night &amp; found that <unclear>Lindsell</unclear>was being married<lb/>
on the 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>Jany to a Miss Hollam?  Daughter of Admiral Hollam<lb/>
 - any relation? - Any how could you send a wedding<lb/>
present to Capt. W Lindsell <hi rend="superscript">RA</hi> Langley House Chichester, choosing<lb/>
 something about 3.00. I have served with him such a <lb/>
lot that I must remember him &amp; if possible I will send <lb/>
a letter later. You can select the  <unclear>idea</unclear> from one of our<lb/>
presents as to what is likely to be useful. Must stop with my<lb/>
 very best Xmas wishes. </p>
        
    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        
            
        

         

